          "body": "Ezekiel 3 opens where chapter 2 left off: the scroll has been presented; now it must be consumed. The command is doubled — 'eat what you find; eat this scroll' (3:1) — and then doubled again when God says 'feed your stomach and fill your body' (3:3). The Hebrew *meeh* (stomach) and *male* (fill) are visceral terms; this is not metaphorical reading but bodily ingestion. The scroll written with lament, mourning, and woe (2:10) must become part of Ezekiel's physiology before it becomes his proclamation. The experience parallels Jeremiah's discovery that God's word was 'a joy and the delight of my heart' (Jeremiah 15:16) and anticipates John's scroll-eating in Revelation 10:9-10 — a moment equally described as sweet in the mouth, bitter in the stomach. The sweetness Ezekiel experiences (3:3) is not the sweetness of the content (lament and woe are not sweet) but of communion with God and obedience to His command. Daniel Block (*The Book of Ezekiel*, NICOT) notes that the sweetness reflects the prophet's willingness, not the message's pleasantness. The pastoral principle is foundational: Ezekiel cannot deliver what he has not digested. The word must be taken into the heart (3:10) before it reaches the tongue."
